Biscoff Stuffed Cookies (makes 20)
Biscoff Centers (make first)
20 tsp Biscoff spread — scoop onto parchment-lined plate/sheet, freeze at least 2 hours (overnight is better)
Dough
	∙	1 cup (2 sticks) unsalted butter, browned and cooled to room temperature
	∙	¾ cup dark brown sugar, packed
	∙	⅓ cup + 1 tbsp granulated sugar
	∙	2 large eggs (1 whole + 1 yolk for extra richness)
	∙	2 tsp vanilla extract
	∙	⅓ cup Biscoff spread
	∙	2½ cups all-purpose flour (spoon & level — don’t scoop)
	∙	1 tsp baking soda
	∙	½ tsp baking powder
	∙	1 tsp fine sea salt (not a pinch — salt makes these sing)
	∙	1 tsp cornstarch (keeps centers gooey)
	∙	7 oz white chocolate, roughly chopped (not chips — get a bar like Lindt for better melt and flavor)
	∙	7 oz Biscoff cookies, hand-crushed into varied sizes (some crumbs, some chunks)
Instructions
	1.	Brown the butter. Melt butter in a saucepan over medium heat, swirling occasionally, until it smells nutty and the milk solids are golden amber. Pour into a heatproof bowl and cool to room temp (about 30 min, or fridge 15 min). This is the single biggest upgrade — it adds a deep toffee/caramel note that pairs perfectly with the Biscoff.
	2.	Mix wet ingredients. Whisk brown butter with both sugars until smooth and slightly thick, about 1 minute. Add egg, egg yolk, vanilla, and Biscoff spread. Whisk until emulsified and glossy.
	3.	Combine dry. In a separate bowl, whisk flour, baking soda, baking powder, salt, and cornstarch.
	4.	Fold together. Add dry to wet, fold with a spatula until just barely combined — a few flour streaks are fine. Fold in chopped white chocolate and crushed Biscoff cookies. Do not overmix.
	5.	Rest the dough. Cover and refrigerate at least 2 hours, ideally 24–36 hours. This hydrates the flour, deepens flavor, and gives you a better texture with more contrast between crispy edges and a chewy center.
	6.	Assemble. Scoop about 3 tbsp of dough, flatten in your palm, place a frozen Biscoff center in the middle, and wrap the dough around it, sealing completely. Roll into a ball.
	7.	Chill again. Place assembled balls on a parchment-lined sheet and chill 30 min to 1 hour before baking. Cold dough = less spread = thicker cookies.
	8.	Bake. Preheat oven to 350°F (180°C). Space cookies 3 inches apart. Bake 12–14 minutes — edges should be set and golden, centers should look slightly underdone and puffy. They’ll firm up as they cool.
	9.	Shape & finish. Immediately after pulling from the oven, use a round cookie cutter or the back of a spoon to gently swirl/push the edges inward for a perfect round shape. Press a few reserved white chocolate chunks and Biscoff cookie pieces into the tops while still warm. Sprinkle with a tiny pinch of flaky sea salt (Maldon).
